WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.300
 Hello, and welcome to another walkthrough for Django for everybody.

00:00:05.300 --> 00:00:11.400
 In this walkthrough, we are going to talk about the browser debugger console.

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:16.360
 And so this is something that in the old days was only in Firefox, but eventually everybody

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:17.360
 built it in.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:20.160
 They used to have to build a plugin.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:22.460
 And it shows up at different places.

00:00:22.460 --> 00:00:25.280
 And so in Firefox, it's here under Tools.

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:32.680
 It turns out that you can kind of go to any of these things, because these are just different

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:34.240
 tabs here.

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:40.320
 In Chrome, we do View, Developer, JavaScript Console.

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:44.440
 And then you see a similar kind of thing here.

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:51.360
 So I'm going to do it in Firefox here.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:55.720
 And so you can see things like you can see the document object model, you can see the

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:57.440
 JavaScript console.

00:00:57.440 --> 00:00:59.080
 This little error hardly matters.

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:00.920
 It's because it's such a simple page.

00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:02.760
 You can actually debug JavaScript code.

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:04.440
 You can watch the network.

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:10.160
 You can play with CSS, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:12.160
 Performance cookies are in here.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:16.320
 So there's a lot of things that you can do.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:20.600
 I'm going to start and show you right now, we're at the very beginning class, I'm just

00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:23.480
 going to show you some of the most basic things here.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:28.360
 I'm going to clear this out.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:30.880
 And then refresh the page.

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:35.880
 And so what you see here is you see each request response cycle.

00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:40.640
 And so I came up here as if I typed this-- let me clear it again so you see it.

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:41.640
 I'm going to type this.

00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:43.400
 I'm going to press Enter.

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:46.120
 And that tells the browser to go retrieve this page.

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:52.280
 So it connects to the server, www.DrChuck.com, and gets the document page 1.htm.

00:01:52.280 --> 00:01:56.720
 This favicon.ico, that's basically getting this little favicon right here.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:01.640
 That's the little thing that shows up in the tab bar.

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:06.160
 And so websites can have a file, and later we will actually make a favicon.

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:10.360
 But what I want to show you from a request response cycle is you can see some detail

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:11.540
 here.

00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:13.600
 So let's go up here.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:15.700
 And you can see detail.

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:18.200
 You can see that this was the URL.

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:20.840
 We sent a request, a get request.

00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:23.680
 We got back a status code.

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:24.880
 Status is the first thing.

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:26.160
 200 isn't OK.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:28.480
 404 is not found.

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:31.400
 And we used HTTP version 1.1.

00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:37.680
 The request headers-- they always show you the request headers, response headers first.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:42.640
 So these request headers are actually part of the HTTP protocol where we are telling

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:52.420
 things like what my preferred language is, what kind of documents we can handle, and

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:53.880
 cookies that we're sending back in.

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:55.680
 We'll learn more about all of this stuff.

00:02:55.680 --> 00:03:01.280
 And so this is actually-- the browser makes the connection to port 80, sends the get request

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:10.120
 to the URL it's interested in, get HTTP www.DrChuck.com/page1.htm, space HTTP 1.1.

00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:14.560
 And then after it, it sends these-- and this is pretty much the format, except colon, blah,

00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:15.800
 blah, blah.

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:19.560
 And so that is the-- and then it sends an empty line.

00:03:19.560 --> 00:03:20.560
 And then it's done.

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:25.560
 And then the browser sends back first a set of headers.

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:27.480
 What the content type is very important.

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.120
 The size is sometimes in here.

00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:34.840
 Gzip means that it compressed it on the way.

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:37.280
 And so these are the response headers.

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:53.240
 And so if I go to an error page, not a page.htm, I'm going to clear this.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:04:00.120
 And what's happening here is it's putting up a page from my hosting system.

00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:04.740
 But the most important one here is this, and that is the 404 error.

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:11.000
 And so it was going and it sent a get request to HTTP.DrChuck.com, not a page.htm.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.320
 And it got back a 404 not found.

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:18.720
 So that was the-- that 404 not found is a different status code that said this is a

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:19.720
 thing that's not there.

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:21.800
 500 means the server had an error.

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:23.120
 And we'll talk about all these codes.

00:04:23.120 --> 00:04:29.040
 But the point is, is you can debug all this stuff quite nicely.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:35.480
 So let me go back to page 1.htm.

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:38.320
 Let's clear this and refresh it to make sure we got it all right.

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:40.400
 OK, so we grabbed the page.

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:44.980
 And now I can-- another thing that you probably by now have figured out to be able to do is

00:04:44.980 --> 00:04:46.640
 inspect element.

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:50.040
 So now you're actually looking at this document object model, right?

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:56.120
 And so this document object model is not necessarily the code that came back from the server.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:05:02.080
 If I go here to network and I click on Get and I look at the response, this is the response

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:03.480
 down here.

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:05.840
 This is what actually came back from the server.

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:10.880
 And then the browser parses this and turns it into what's called the document object

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:11.880
 model.

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:13.200
 So this is the source.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:22.440
 Now just as for fun here, you'll notice that I can change the document object model here.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:27.760
 If you are cool, you can switch to the second page.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:31.280
 So you'll notice the document object model changed and what I saw up here changed as

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:32.280
 well.

00:05:32.280 --> 00:05:34.040
 And so this is like inspect element.

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:36.920
 I can do something like I can even add here.

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:43.640
 I can add some CSS, style equals color, colon, red, semicolon.

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:45.400
 And if all goes well, there you go.

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:47.080
 You see I switched the color.

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:48.840
 This is the document object model.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:50.960
 Now the server was completely uninvolved in that.

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:55.320
 And later we're going to write a lot of code to mess with the document object model.

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:58.360
 So the server is still-- it doesn't have the red in here.

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:00.280
 It didn't change this to cool.

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:03.040
 So this is what we originally got from the server.

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:05.320
 And this is what we've got in the browser.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:11.300
 And so once that page comes from the server, you or JavaScript can mess with that page.

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:13.600
 So it's pretty dang cool.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:14.600
 OK.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:16.040
 So I'm going to clear it.

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:19.600
 And I'm just going to click on the second page, which is an anchor.

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:20.600
 Let's inspect it.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:21.900
 Well, it's an anchor tag.

00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:23.800
 And so it's going to do another get request.

00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:25.840
 And so this time it went and grabbed page two.

00:06:25.840 --> 00:06:27.760
 And there's the second page.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:30.520
 And you can go back to the first page.

00:06:30.520 --> 00:06:34.640
 And so there's a lot of things that you can see.

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:37.360
 This persist logs is an important feature.

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:40.360
 That means that it keeps them crossed more than one request.

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:43.320
 And disable cache means that sometimes the browser

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:45.340
 wants to keep a copy of something.

00:06:45.340 --> 00:06:47.720
 And you, while you're debugging, you want to say, hey, go

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:51.480
 get the original every time.

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:55.440
 And so right now I'm giving you-- starting you on very simple pages.

00:06:55.440 --> 00:07:02.280
 But if you take a more complex page, and I can never remember where it is.

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:03.880
 View, developer, network.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:05.320
 Let's go here.

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:08.560
 If you take a more complex page with a bunch of things in it,

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:12.200
 and you hit refresh on this page, you will see that it does a get request.

00:07:12.200 --> 00:07:17.600
 But then as it parses that get request, it finds things like all kinds of stuff.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:25.160
 So here this took 44 request response cycles, 1.6 megabytes.

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:29.440
 And it took almost one second to download all that stuff.

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:32.640
 It took a second to download it.

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:34.960
 And so if you go, you scroll all the way up to the top.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:38.800
 The original get request was to this URL, which

00:07:38.800 --> 00:07:42.320
 is /lessons/rrc, which is the URL.

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:45.240
 But then if you were to look at the response--

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:46.400
 and I don't want to see that.

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:47.780
 I want to see the actual HTML.

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:53.360
 So if you look at the response, you see all these URLs

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:57.840
 for more stuff, some CSS from JavaScript, some who knows what.

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:01.720
 And so then what you see is you see it then retrieving all these other things

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:06.800
 that it needs to actually construct the page, some CSS.

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:11.600
 Grabbed a font, it grabbed jQuery, it grabbed time ago.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:13.200
 That's a little thing like--

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:16.160
 and then grabbed a bunch of JavaScript, and fonts, and this.

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:19.080
 And then the translate-- so you see this little translate thing?

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:19.960
 It's doing that.

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:22.840
 And so you'll see that's how it quickly builds up

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:29.240
 to about 44 request response cycles to produce a page.

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:33.680
 Now, so that's just my quick introduction to this.

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:37.920
 You may not see these little dropdowns like this.

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:40.000
 You might have to turn them on in Preferences.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.660
 So you go into Preferences somewhere.

00:08:41.660 --> 00:08:43.040
 I turned them on a long time ago.

00:08:43.040 --> 00:08:45.760
 I probably couldn't even find it, but you might see it.

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:51.320
 The other thing that I would suggest is don't use Safari,

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:59.640
 because Safari is trying to hide too much stuff.

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:02.240
 It doesn't even show you the URL unless you click on it.

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:05.880
 So Safari is kind of a pain in the neck.

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:10.280
 And so I would suggest that for this class, you either use Firefox

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:13.560
 or you use Chrome in addition to using Safari.

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:17.240
 Safari is fine for daily use, but I just find it as a debugger.

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:20.400
 It's bad, which is really sad for Safari.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:25.120
 They made Safari unfriendly to software developers,

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:28.000
 which means we're not going to test our stuff on Safari, which

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.800
 means if it breaks, too bad.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:35.160
 So OK, well, enough of that little Safari diatribe.

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:38.800
 Again, I hope that you found this walkthrough for Django

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:40.720
 for everybody as usual helpful.

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:42.280
 Cheers.

